#1 Resected stage IIIB ascending colon carcinoma
Patient underwent right hemicolectomy on April 7, 2010, for a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of the ascending colon which extended focally into the visceral peritoneum making it a T4 lesion.  There were 3 of 13 metastatic regional lymph nodes.  There is no obvious metastatic disease, and the patient has a hemangioma in the liver.
I discussed with Mrs. Harpole my recommendation or systemic adjuvant chemotherapy with the modified FOLFOX6 regimen.  Patient will need a Port-A-Cath for this treatment, and I will arrange general surgery consultation.  The recommendation for 12 cycles of treatment was reviewed with chemotherapy given every two-weeks.  The patient does have some residual neuropathy from prior chemotherapy related to breast cancer.  Therefore, we will initiate treatment with oxaliplatin but carefully monitor her for worsening peripheral neuropathy and make modifications as-needed.  Other potential side-effects of treatment were reviewed with the patient and her husband.  We will plan to initiate chemotherapy this week.
#2 Advanced colonic adenomas
The patient's colonoscopy demonstrated adenomas of the ascending and sigmoid colon in addition to the right colonic carcinoma.  She had not had prior colonoscopy.  There were three polyps in the sigmoid colon measuring 8, 5, and 2-mm, and pathology demonstrated tubular adenoma with high-grade dysplasia.  I am recommending repeat colonoscopy in six-months for further evaluation of the polypectomy site.  There is no known family history of colorectal cancer in this patient's family.  The pathology report did indicate that the appendix was involved by a sessile serrated adenoma.  These can develop within the microsatellite instability pathway.  Accordingly, I will request the pathologist to test the primary colon carcinoma for DNA mismatch repair protein expression.  There is evidence that these tumors may just demonstrate resistance to 5-FU.
#3 History of stage IIIA breast cancer
Treatment details are as outlined above.  Patient has completed five years of Arimidex therapy.  She is followed by Dr. Cottman in Medical Oncology.
#4 Peripheral neuropathy, likely chemotherapy related
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: Yes, on file at Baptist Medical Center.

