Stage III colon carcinoma.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

Mrs. Warren is a 67-year-old woman from California North Dakota, who underwent right hemicolectomy on April 7, 2010, for a stage III adenocarcinoma of the ascending colon.  Pathologic examination demonstrated moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma with focal extension to the visceral peritoneum, and 3 of 13 metastatic regional lymph nodes.  The patient is now approximately four weeks status-post surgical resection and has recovered well.  She denies abdominal pain and is not taking pain medication.  Her bowels move daily, and there is no blood in the stool.  Of note, her colonoscopy done preoperatively was for iron-deficiency anemia, and she had not had prior colonoscopy.  This examination demonstrated a cecal mass in addition to adenomatous polyps of the ascending colon and sigmoid.  The report describes sigmoid polyps measuring 8-mm, 5-mm, and 2-mm, the larger polyps being removed by snare polypectomy, and the smaller being biopsied.  Pathology demonstrated fragments of tubular adenoma with high-grade dysplasia and hyperplastic polyp; all of these were from the sigmoid colon.  The patient also has a history of stage IIIA breast cancer in left breast which was infiltrating ductal adenocarcinoma positive for ER and PR but negative for HER-2.  She was treated with lumpectomy, axillary dissection, radiation, and systemic chemotherapy with Adriamycin, Cytoxan, and Taxol.  She had also completed five years of Arimidex therapy.  She if followed by Dr. Rodney Cottman in TMC.
Patient indicates that she has had some residual neuropathy following chemotherapy for breast cancer.  She reports numbness and tingling in her feet which has persisted, and she previously took Neurontin 300-mg t.i.d. without benefit.  She indicated it does not interfere with her ambulation.

[end section id="20103"]

